explanation:
Why each symbol is needed to decide whether any code in OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew is unreachable:

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The function’s conditional branches use (operation_status == OS_SUCCESS). To determine if either branch is statically impossible (and thus unreachable) the value/definition of OS_SUCCESS must be known.

- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED
  - Used in the else branch to assign final_id. Knowing its definition (value/semantics) can be relevant to decide whether that assignment or subsequent uses are meaningful or optimized-away in whole-program analysis.

- OS_object_token_t
  - The token->obj_id member is accessed when operation_status == OS_SUCCESS. The token type/definition is needed to confirm that this access is valid and whether token is constrained by callers (e.g. always non-NULL), which can affect reachability of the branch.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish
  - Called unconditionally before later code. If this function does not return (e.g. longjmp, abort, infinite loop) or it changes program state in a way that makes subsequent statements unreachable, that must be detected by inspecting its implementation.

- OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken, OS_Lock_Global, OS_Unlock_Global
  - These are callees of OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish (from the static graph). They must be examined to determine whether OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish can fail to return or otherwise make later code unreachable or to see side-effects on final_id or global state that affect reachability.

- OS_NotifyEvent
  - Called conditionally when operation_status == OS_SUCCESS. If OS_NotifyEvent never returns or has side-effects making following code unreachable, that affects reachability of later statements. Its definition/behavior must be known.

- All direct callers of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew (listed below)
  - OS_BinSemCreate, OS_CondVarCreate, OS_CountSemCreate, OS_DirectoryOpen, OS_OpenCreate, OS_FileSys_Initialize, OS_FileSysAddFixedMap, OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew, OS_ModuleLoad, OS_MutSemCreate, OS_ConsoleAPI_Init, OS_QueueCreate, OS_SocketOpen, OS_SocketAccept, OS_TaskCreate, OS_TimeBaseCreate, OS_DoTimerAdd
  - To decide whether either branch inside OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew is unreachable in the whole project, each call site must be inspected to see what values they actually pass for operation_status (e.g. always OS_SUCCESS, always an error code, or a variable). A branch that is never taken at all call sites would be project-level unreachable code in violation of MISRA.

Summary: To determine unreachable code you must know the constant values used in the comparisons (OS_SUCCESS, OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED), the token type/constraints, whether the unconditional transaction finish call or the notify call can prevent return, and what concrete values callers pass for operation_status. The listed symbols cover these required definitions and call-sites.
